# 3. Authentication & Identity Management Architecture

## 3.1 Objective

The authentication architecture is designed to provide:

* Secure enterprise login
* Centralized identity management
* Single Sign-On (SSO)
* Multi-factor authentication (MFA)
* Automated user provisioning
* Group-based access control
* Centralized governance and auditing

Google Workspace acts as the centralized Identity Provider (IdP).

Databricks relies on Google Workspace for:

* User authentication
* User lifecycle management
* Group synchronization
* Role mapping

---

# 4. Authentication Flow

## 4.1 End-to-End Authentication Flow

The following steps describe the authentication process.

### Step 1 – User Opens Databricks Workspace

The user accesses the Databricks workspace URL.

Example:

[https://holcim-prod.cloud.databricks.com](https://holcim-prod.cloud.databricks.com)

---

### Step 2 – Databricks Redirects User to Google Login

Since SSO is enabled, Databricks redirects the user to Google Workspace authentication.

Databricks does not manage local passwords.

Authentication is delegated to Google Workspace.

---

### Step 3 – User Authenticates Using Google Credentials

The user enters enterprise Google Workspace credentials.

Enterprise security controls are enforced:

* MFA
* Password policies
* Device policies
* Session controls
* Conditional access

---

### Step 4 – Google Sends SAML Assertion to Databricks

After successful authentication, Google Workspace sends a signed SAML assertion to Databricks.

The assertion contains:

* User identity
* Email
* User attributes
* Group information
* Authentication status

---

### Step 5 – Databricks Validates SAML Assertion

Databricks validates:

* Signature authenticity
* Token validity
* Trusted Identity Provider
* User mapping

If validation succeeds, access is granted.

---

### Step 6 – Workspace Access Granted

The user gains access to the appropriate Databricks workspace.

Actual data access is controlled separately through:

* Unity Catalog
* Groups
* Catalog permissions
* Schema permissions
* Table permissions

---

# 5. SAML-Based Single Sign-On (SSO)

## 5.1 Why SAML is Used

SAML 2.0 is used to enable enterprise-grade Single Sign-On.

Benefits:

* Centralized authentication
* No local Databricks passwords
* Enterprise MFA enforcement
* Simplified user experience
* Improved security posture
* Easier auditing and compliance

---

## 5.2 Databricks SSO Configuration

The following configuration is typically performed in the Databricks Account Console.

### Databricks SSO Configuration Steps

1. Enable SAML Authentication
2. Upload Google IdP metadata
3. Configure Assertion Consumer Service (ACS) URL
4. Configure Entity ID
5. Configure redirect URLs
6. Configure user attribute mapping
7. Validate trust relationship

---

## 5.3 Google Workspace Configuration

The following configuration is typically performed in Google Admin Console.

### Google Workspace SAML Configuration Steps

1. Create custom SAML application
2. Configure Databricks ACS URL
3. Configure Entity ID
4. Configure Name ID mapping
5. Configure attribute mappings
6. Enable application for users/groups

Mapped attributes typically include:

| Attribute | Purpose             |
| --------- | ------------------- |
| email     | User identification |
| firstName | User profile        |
| lastName  | User profile        |
| groups    | Access management   |

---

# 6. SCIM Provisioning Architecture

## 6.1 Purpose of SCIM

SSO handles authentication only.

SCIM is used for:

* User provisioning
* User deprovisioning
* Group synchronization
* Automated onboarding/offboarding
* Role and access synchronization

Without SCIM:

* Users must be manually created
* Groups must be manually managed
* Offboarding becomes operationally difficult
* Governance risks increase

---

## 6.2 SCIM Provisioning Flow

### Step 1 – User Created in Google Workspace

A new enterprise user is created in Google Workspace.

---

### Step 2 – SCIM Sync Triggered

SCIM automatically synchronizes:

* User identity
* Group memberships
* Access mappings

---

### Step 3 – User Created in Databricks

The user is automatically provisioned in Databricks.

No manual administration required.

---

### Step 4 – Group Memberships Assigned

Users inherit access based on enterprise groups.

Example:

| Google Group           | Databricks Access       |
| ---------------------- | ----------------------- |
| grp_dlk_finance_read   | Finance read access     |
| grp_dlk_sales_write    | Sales write access      |
| grp_dlk_platform_admin | Platform administration |

---

### Step 5 – Automatic Deactivation

When users leave the organization:

* Google account is disabled
* SCIM removes access automatically
* Databricks access revoked

This ensures governance compliance.

---

# 7. Recommended Access Control Model

## 7.1 Enterprise RBAC (Role-Based Access Control)

The platform follows a group-based RBAC model.

Best practice:

* No direct user permissions
* Permissions granted only to groups
* Centralized group management
* Least privilege principle

---

## 7.2 Recommended Access Hierarchy

The recommended hierarchy is:

User
→ Google Group
→ Databricks Group
→ Unity Catalog Permission
→ Data Access

---

## 7.3 Example Group Naming Standards

Recommended naming convention:

| Group Name              | Purpose                 |
| ----------------------- | ----------------------- |
| grp_dlk_finance_read    | Finance read access     |
| grp_dlk_finance_write   | Finance write access    |
| grp_dlk_sales_read      | Sales read access       |
| grp_dlk_ds_ml_engineers | ML engineering access   |
| grp_dlk_platform_admin  | Platform administration |

This approach improves:

* Governance
* Auditability
* Automation
* CI/CD integration
* Operational scalability

