# 11. Unity Catalog Governance Model

## 11.1 Purpose of Unity Catalog

Unity Catalog acts as the centralized governance layer.

It provides:

* Centralized access control
* Data governance
* Lineage tracking
* Audit logging
* Fine-grained permissions
* Data discovery

---

## 11.2 Governance Philosophy

The architecture follows:

Data-centric governance
instead of
Workspace-centric governance.

Meaning:

Data security is controlled at:

* Catalog level
* Schema level
* Table level
* Row level
* Column level

---

## 11.3 Recommended Catalog Structure

Example:

| Catalog               | Domain                     |
| --------------------- | -------------------------- |
| finance_catalog       | Finance                    |
| sales_catalog         | Sales                      |
| manufacturing_catalog | Manufacturing              |
| shared_catalog        | Shared enterprise datasets |

---

## 11.4 Recommended Schema Structure

Within each catalog:

| Schema  | Purpose                 |
| ------- | ----------------------- |
| raw     | Raw ingestion data      |
| silver  | Cleansed data           |
| gold    | Business-ready data     |
| sandbox | Analyst experimentation |

---

# 12. Recommended Permission Strategy

## 12.1 Catalog-Level Permissions

Example responsibilities:

* Finance users access finance catalog
* Sales users access sales catalog

---

## 12.2 Schema-Level Permissions

Controls access to:

* Raw data
* Curated layers
* Sandbox areas

---

## 12.3 Table-Level Permissions

Provides fine-grained control for:

* Sensitive tables
* Restricted datasets
* Operational datasets

---

## 12.4 Row-Level and Column-Level Security

Recommended for:

* Regional restrictions
* Sensitive financial data
* HR information
* Compliance requirements

Examples:

* APAC users only see APAC data
* Salary columns masked
* Vendor users access restricted datasets only

---

# 13. IAM Role-Based Storage Access

## 13.1 Recommended Security Model

The platform should use IAM role-based access.

Databricks accesses S3 through:

* IAM roles
* Storage credentials
* External locations

---

## 13.2 Important Security Principle

No direct user access to S3.

Users should access data only through:

* Databricks
* Unity Catalog
* Governed access controls

This improves:

* Security
* Governance
* Auditing
* Data protection

---

# 14. Service Principals & Automation

## 14.1 Purpose

Service principals should be used for:

* Airflow orchestration
* CI/CD pipelines
* dbt execution
* Automated jobs
* APIs

---

## 14.2 Best Practice

Avoid using personal user accounts for automation.

Use dedicated service identities.

Examples:

| Service Principal | Purpose               |
| ----------------- | --------------------- |
| svc_airflow_prod  | Airflow orchestration |
| svc_dbt_prod      | dbt execution         |
| svc_ci_cd         | Deployment pipelines  |

---

# 15. Recommended Governance Best Practices

## 15.1 Core Recommendations

The recommended enterprise best practices are:

* Separate workspaces per environment
* Separate S3 buckets per environment
* Centralized Unity Catalog governance
* Google SSO + SCIM
* Group-based RBAC
* IAM role-based storage access
* No direct user access to S3
* Least privilege access model
* Automated provisioning
* Audit logging enabled
* Row/column security for sensitive data

---

